<DOC><DOCNO> AP880521-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0819EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea     05-21 0427</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea,0443</SECOND><HEAD>Police Hunt For Masterminds Behind U.S. Embassy Attack</HEAD><BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police hunted today for radicalleaders suspected of key roles in a bomb attack on the U.S. Embassyin Seoul. Anti-government protests continued.   Police officials said a search was under way for radicalsbelieved to be behind the attack Friday on the embassy, wherestudents scaled the walls and hurled homemade bombs.   Radical students resumed demonstrations today against thegovernment of President Roh Tae-woo and the United States afterfour days of fierce clashes between protesters and riot police.Most of the demonstrations were peaceful.   Police remained on nationwide alert and riot police squadsguarded key locations in Seoul and other cities.   Students and dissidents demanding the overthrow of Roh havebattled riot police with firebombs and rocks in the streets ofSeoul and other cities. The violence is the worst political unrestsince major riots last summer.   Investigators said the embassy attack apparently was organizedby radicals responsible for other attacks on U.S. diplomaticoffices and offices of the governing Democratic Justice Party.   Seven students arrested in the embassy attack were beingquestioned by police, they said.   The police officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, saidat least 20 other students were suspected of plotting the attackand they believed a student leader named Kim Chul was involved.   Kim is wanted for a Feb. 24 attack on the U.S. InformationService building in Seoul by radicals who exploded bombs andbriefly seized the building.   Protesters broke windows and hurled several firebombs at thesame building during clashes on Thursday.   In the embassy attack, students wielding iron bars and hurlinghomemade bombs scaled the walls and clashed with police in thecompound. One police officer and two students were hurt.   The bombs did not cause any damage to the embassy building, butthe policeman sustained blast wounds.   Anti-U.S. sentiment has been running high in the recent wave ofanti-government protests. Radicals claim the Roh government is keptin power by the United States.   Protesters have burned American flags, attacked U.S. diplomaticbuildings and demanded the removal of about 42,000 U.S. troopsbased in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.   In the southern city of Kwangju, police remained on full alerttoday following four days of violent anti-government and anti-U.S.protests marking the anniversary of a 1980 civilian uprising. Atleast 191 people died in the uprising.   Tens of thousands of citizens and students have been stagingrallies in Kwangju, shouting anti-government and anti-U.S. slogans.</TEXT></DOC>